Hi, we just published `hadhat@2.2.0`, which upgrades the VM and adds support for Berlin. Before releasing it, we ran our tests in several popular projects that use Hardhat to make sure that everything works fine.

When we did that in Uniswaps' repo, we noticed that a lot of tests fail now because they check that the used gas matches some given value. So this is just a friendly warning that that will happen when you upgrade. If you want to temporarily keep the previous behavior, you just need to do this in your config:

```javascript
networks: {
  hardhat: {
    hardfork: "muirGlacier"
  }
}
```

The `swap` function has the `lock` modifier but explicitly resets the lock [here](https://github.com/Uniswap/uniswap-v3-core/blob/83ddb278c6323b908d61d4c8e891ff842efac9b9/contracts/UniswapV3Pool.sol#L686).

Is this intentional? Without the optimizer enabled, this would seem to incur a 1500 gas extra gas cost (from a quick test). With it enabled to the 800 runs as defined by hardhat config, the difference goes away. Removing it does seemingly save about 7 bytes per deployment, which is about 1400 gas per pool deployment (in a simple test deployment that explores explicitly whether to have that line or not). I haven't tested with the full contract.

Here is the sample code:
```
contract T {
    modifier lock() {
        slot0.unlocked = false;
        _;
        slot0.unlocked = true;
    }
    
    struct Slot0 {
        bool unlocked;
    }
    
    Slot0 slot0;
    
    constructor() public {
        slot0.unlocked = true;
    }
    function t() public lock returns (int256, int256) {
        slot0.unlocked = true;
        return (0, 0);
    }
    
    
}

contract T2 {
    modifier lock() {
        slot0.unlocked = false;
        _;
        slot0.unlocked = true;
    }
    
    struct Slot0 {
        bool unlocked;
    }
    
    Slot0 slot0;
    
    constructor() public {
        slot0.unlocked = true;
    }
    
    function t() public lock returns (int256, int256) {
        return (0, 0);
    }
}
```

